[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Watts Ley is a delightful 89-year-old hard-of-hearing gentleman recently found to have advanced colon adenocarcinoma who has undertaken resection of a cecal primary tumor but was found to have extensive hepatic metastases at surgery that could not be resected.  The patient has a prior history of comorbidity including coronary artery disease with direct interventions to the heart as recently as this past September.  He has also had peripheral vascular disease and claudication and also significant chronic renal insufficiency with most recent creatinine determinations consistently over 3-mg/dL.
Most recently, the patient was found to have a cecal mass.  Resection was undertaken by Dr. Thompson with, unfortunately, multiple metastases found at surgery, albeit not so apparent on noncontrast CT-scan which was required because of the patient's chronic renal failure.  The patient now presents to us for an opinion with regard to options for palliative therapy.

[end section id="20103"]

